	<div id="about" style="margin-top:40px;">
		<!-- h3 style="margin-bottom: 5px"> About Me </h3 -->
		I work at IBM's <a href="http://www.research.ibm.com/labs/watson/">TJ Watson Research Center</a>, where I study and develop algorithms for natural language processing. I got my PhD in 2016 from the <a href="http://www.colorado.edu/cs/">Department of Computer Science at University of Colorado Boulder</a>, advised by Professor <a href="http://spot.colorado.edu/~sumner/">Tammy Sumner</a>.
	</div>

	<div id="research_interests" style="margin-top:30px;">
		<h3 style="margin-bottom: 5px"> Research </h3>
		I am primarily interested in computational models of textual semantics.
		In the past, I have worked on short-text semantic similarity and alignment, and applied text similarity models to solve real-world problems such as question answering and short answer grading, and also explored their data-driven adaptation to different information and application domains.
		At IBM, I have worked so far mostly on question answering. 
		My research plans for the near future revolve around compositional vector representations of sentences, a primary objective being to support real-world NLP tasks across different domains and applications.
	</div>
		
